column49: The principal activities of the Association during the financial year were: 1. To function as a non-profit association whose Members comprise Volunteer Fire Brigades registered by the Country Fire Authority under the Country Fire Authority Act (1958) and its Regulations. 2. To liaise and consult on the operation of the 'Volunteer Charter' in the interests of CFA volunteers about all matters which might reasonably be expected to affect them. The Volunteer Charter is an agreed tripartite commitment between the State of Victoria, the CFA, and CFA Volunteers, committing the State of Victoria and the CFA to consultation with volunteers about all matters which might reasonably be expected to affect volunteers. VBFV represents its Members and CFA Volunteers in that consultation process. 3. To assist in maintaining high morale, ongoing health and welfare of CFA volunteer members and their families 4. Support CFA volunteers experiencing personal financial hardship/crisis by providing small welfare grants that may assist in alleviating stresses impacting on the individual's ability to maintain their involvement as a volunteer. 5. Preserve and strengthen CFA's community and volunteer based foundations by enabling members of CFA brigades to consider and bring to the notice of CFA all matters affecting their welfare and efficiency (other than questions of discipline and promotion). 6. To promote to CFA volunteers the comprehensive support services available to them including but not limited to: legal assistance, OH&S, equity and diversity, counselling and welfare, training, employment support and compensation for accidents, injuries and illness.7. To develop awareness, respect and support for CFA volunteers and their fundamental and pivotal role in the CFA as a community based, volunteer based fire and emergency service for the people of Victoria.  8. To take any other action as determined by the Association Board consistent with these purposes.9. To maintain and pursue a balanced focus on issues affecting CFA volunteers across all brigades from all risk profiles.

column2: Iglesia De La Profecia Nueva Rosa De Saron Inc
column49: The church works to promote love, peace, unity, giving and helping within the community as well as focusing on promoting family, youth, children's well being and togetherness.  It also provides activities to help the church communicate and interact with other local churches to encourage culture and community unity.  Where possible it provides financial and emotional support to all members and community members in need of support in any given circumstance to help them through their hardship.  The church conducts weekly church services, prayers, band practice and musical training, youth group and meetings, as well as community meetings and gathering.  These are all open to the wider community and those in need of support and assistance.  The church has been providing the above services for the last thirty years throughout Melbourne being primarily based in the western suburbs and focused largely on the Spanish community.  However anyone is welcome to join and attend and there is English translation at all events and programs. The church is currently based at 6-8 Henderson Street, North Sunshine, Victoria 3020 and have been since 2009.

column2: Piers K Fowler Scholarship Fund Ltd
column49: Report for the Year to June, 2016:  Year 3Piers passed away on 4th June 2013.  We miss him.  We miss his basic goodness and kindness and talents and warmth.  The family's aim in establishing this Scholarship Fund and an associated Trust has been to invest Piers' own assets for donating to recognised educational and charitable institutions associated with his life.  Piers was a senior training pilot with Qantas so our first aim has been to donate in the area of aviation education and training.  Piers also had volunteer involvement with the Salvation Army, Arthritis Victoria, and Scienceworks.  He was concerned for disadvantaged children and their education, and for homeless people.  He was an organ donor.  All of the things which represent Piers guide the work of the Scholarship Fund and its associated Trust, the Piers K Fowler Trust.  Details relating to the Fund may be found on the website of the Australian Charities and Not for Profits Commission (ACNC).  The Fund must deal specifically with scholarships.  The Trust may distribute benefits more widely but always to DGR-recognised institutions and always to the benefits which Piers would have sought.  The Fund and Trust together made donations of just over $90,000 in this latest financial year, bringing total donations and grants since inception to almost $200,000.  As in the previous year, our donations and gifts were virtually equal to the income earned during the year.  Reflecting Piers' own life, Aviation education, training and development forms a major part of the Fund's work.  We have a wide-ranging program of aviation-related Scholarships and awards with Swinburne University of Technology (SUT), including one overseas exchange award, support for an instructor rating course, a research award and a number of development / leadership awards.  We also support the SUT Mentoring Program for aviation students developed by Captain Mark Kreiger of Qantas.  Similarly, with the Aviation School of RMIT University, we provide a number of scholarships plus funds to support a Technical Library for all students.  We express our thanks to SUT and RMIT for their support and guidance in establishing our scholarship programs.  In other activities, the Trust is involved with Museum Victoria in the establishment of an interactive aviation-related display at Scienceworks.  Additionally, The Trust continues to support 15 Smith Family children and has provided funding to Melbourne City Mission, the Salvation Army and the Lighthouse Foundation in support of training and activity programs for homeless or potentially homeless people.  The Trust has made contributions in support of Move Arthritis Victoria, a Monash Medical School Scholarship, Ovarian Cancer Australia, St Yared a school for children in Ethiopia, and the Indigenous Literary Foundation.We are pleased to accept public donations (which have to be directed through the DGR-approved Scholarship Fund) but will not be seeking to develop that avenu
We were able to offer Scholarships and Bursaries and through effective investment planning increase the corpus of funds for this purpose.

column49: Our organisation runs a series of programs and activities primarily focusing on the promotion the Greek language and culture and the provision of pastoral service via our five churches. In addition we have over 1200 student enrolled in our Greek language classes (both children and adults). We also teach Ancient Greek and Drama with enrolments in the vicinity of 130. We hold the following festivals: Lonsdale Street Festival (100,000 patrons), The Greek Film Festival, Flavours of Greece, Greek writers festival, Storytelling for young children, and live musical performances. We have established support groups for parents whose children attend our Schools, as well as support networks near our churches mainly for the elderly. Our patron are both of a Greek and non Greek background.In addition we assist other Greek organisations both welfare based and regionally based. We provided services that assist recent arrivals from Greece to settle in Melbourne.

The Rail Manufacturing CRC exists to foster, sponsor and direct collaborative research and commercialisation partnerships in the Australian rail manufacturing industry.Funded jointly by participating Australian rail organisations and the Federal Government's Department of Industry, Innovation and Science under its Business Cooperative Research Centres Programme, the Rail Manufacturing CRC drives the development of new products, technologies and supply chain networks to enhance the industry's competitiveness.The Rail Manufacturing CRC supports industry-led rail innovation projects, in turn enabling the development of technologies leading to new opportunities for Australian manufacturers.Furthermore, the Rail Manufacturing CRC is actively working to develop the next generation of experienced postgraduate rail students, with financial support via active project participation, research scholarships and internship placements.

column39: Street OutreachCounsellingLife-skills training
column49: Our purpose is to equip and empower troubled youth, individuals and families to overcome crises and experience full restoration in their hearts and lives. We exist to strengthen, train and influence at-risk youth, individuals and families to reach their full potential and become contributing members of our society. We accomplish this through professional Counselling; life-skills training; street outreach services; support groups; programs for at-risk youth; family mediation; inductions to drug and alcohol rehabilitation and a 24Hr Help-line.Our vision is to see a continual decrease in the overwhelming crises so may individuals and families experience as we impact our society one life at a time. Recipients of our services are individuals and families living in crisis: family breakdown; relationship problems; physical, sexual and emotional abuse; depression; suicidal tendencies; drug and alcohol addictions; anger; and many other life-controlling problems.Our life-skills training is strategically combined with professional counselling, support groups and Outreach services, to ensure a wholistic approach to the care we provide. In every service we provide, our emphasis is to coach and empower individuals to build character and life-skills and address emotional and mental trauma or weakness. For more information, we invite you to read our latest Annual Report, http://www.life-gate.org/Annual-Report.html

column39: The provision of a major prize for Australian women's literature, programs promoting women's writing in the school curriculum and amongst teachers and research and data collection around gender inequality and unconscious bias in literature generally.
column49: TThe Stella Prize called for entries to the 2016 prize and appointed well-qualified judges to assess those entries. The Stella Prize presented its winner, Charlotte Wood, with $50,000 in prize money for her novel, The Natural Way of Things, and presented all 6 shortlisted authors with $2,000 in prize money.                            The Stella Prize also undertook a number of outreach, educational and promotional initiatives to raise the profile of Australian women writers, including a number of events and panel discussions focused on gender equity and literature, the Stella Schools Program, the Girls Write Up program, hands-on writing workshops with students and Professional Development programs with school teachers. The Stella Prize also conducts the Stella Count, which is a data collection and assessment initiative aimed at addressing gender inequality and unconscious bias in literature generally.

We helped secure a state renewable energy target in Victoria (a VRET) of 25% renewable energy by 2020 and 40% by 2025. It is expected to double wind energy capacity in the state by 2020 and triple renewable energy capacity by 2025, creating 10,000 jobs and unlocking a $2.5 billion investment opportunity in the process. It is expected to cut carbon emissions in the state by around 15%.We helped sustain the moratorium on onshore gas drilling in the state of Victoria. FoEA invested considerable time and effort into involvement in the SA Royal Commission into nuclear waste, producing extensive research materials and submissions. We also participated in the SA government's 'Citizens Jury' process as an invited witness.We researched the likely social and environmental implications of synthetic biology and new genetic modification (GM) techniques, to identify potential risks.We worked to ensure that ingredients derived from new technologies such as nanotechnology, synthetic biology and new genetic engineering techniques undergo adequate safety testing.We completed a major research project into pesticide contamination in waterways across Australia. The impacts of many chemicals on freshwater ecosystems (for instance on amphibians) is widely documented.We researched many commonly used chemicals (for instance Simazine) and produced education materials on the impacts on natural ecosystems and ways to reduce harm and/or minimise the use of these chemicals in land management practises.We provided major research support for the Australian Pesticide Map, which highlights which pesticides have been detected across the Australian landscape.We worked to ensure the Regional Planning Scheme for the Atherton Tablelands in far north QLD adequately protected World Heritage listed landscapes from inappropriate development.We helped establish a new initiative called Cassowary Keystone Conservation, which aims to reduce predation on cassowaries and other native wildlife by wild dogs.We helped support the work of Frog Safe, which is a group that researches the cause of the decline in frog numbers, which is mainly attributed to a new class of pesticides.We have been supporting the campaign to eradicate yellow crazy ants which is an invasive foreign pest in the Kuranda and Cairns areas which spreads quickly and eradicates virtually all native species. We worked with plantation owners and managers in a number of states to improve land management and remnant indigenous species within their plantations (through actions like wider buffer zones and wildlife corridors).We engaged with Australian, US and European banks, calling on them to avoid investment in new fossil fuel projects on environmental and human rights grounds.We hold concerns about the possibility some trade agreements to undermine the ability of the government to adequately protect the natural environment. We carried out a range of research, education, lobby and public outreach efforts highlighting dangers of ISD

column39: Advancing the science of astronomy
column49: AAL pursued its charitable purpose of advancing the science of astronomy by allocating, contracting with and supplying funds to organisations for the establishment, development,enhancement or operation of, or for access to, astronomy research infrastructure.AAL invested $10.6M in 2015/16, giving Australian researchers access to facilities worth more than $500M. Over 2900 astronomers used the AAL funded facilities in 2015/16, of whom 54% were Australian-based researchers and 46% were international collaborators.In 2015/16, AAL provided funding under the National Collaborative Research Infrastructure Scheme to keep critical facilities, such as the Murchison Widefield Array and gSTAR GPUpowered supercomputer, operating. Funding was also provided for the Australian Square Kilometre Array Pathfinder and access to overseas telescopes.Further funding was provided for development and operation of the All-Sky Virtual Observatory, which was mainly funded by the National eResearch Collaboration Tools and Resources.Access to AAL-supported facilities resulted in publication of 313 refereed journal papers from collaborative research projects, with 80% of the publications involving Australian-international collaborations. These publications span a wide range of astronomical fields, including radio, optical, theoretical, and high-energy astrophysics.Details of AAL activities are in the 2015/16 Annual Report athttp://astronomyaustralia.org.au/files/publications/combined%20file%20for%20web.pdf

Support GroupsWeekly catch ups are essential to continuing to open our hearts and minds to others each Friday at our headquarters in Croydon. This gives everyone the opportunity to chat about the important transitional phases they may be facing and relate to others whilst picking up skills on how to handle these life changing circumstances in a healthy way. Anyone is welcome to join us in conversation and morning tea. Additional groups for parents, partners and family days are organised throughout the year and an annual camp. Housing ProgramWe offer shared living facilities in two locations in Croydon for easy commuting.Elisha Care wear the costs associated with running the houses and take less than 75% of the average cost of a rental from each housemate. This does not cover rental expenses, utilities and upkeep therefore relying heavily on donations to the ongoing success of the program. Some of our applicants come directly from Jail or rehabilitation centres where they do not have the rental history required to get their own accommodation. Each successful applicant that we house (maximum 8 beds) must contribute to daily tasks and adhere to our strict house rules. Each person is assigned a buddy that can be their support day or night.Volunteer ProgramElisha Care started this program 4 years ago and is one of our biggest successes in rehabilitating the men in our network. We have two established teams working a 4 day week on garden and building maintenance jobs booked in the local area. The team has been generously supported by donated vehicles, trailers and tools to carry out requests by residential and commercial clientele. The efforts to rehabilitate our members with daily purpose and support has been a huge success in their recovery. Uniforms, Insurance, equipment and training are a few of the many ongoing expenses that can be managed through ongoing bookings and donations from the public. The financial expenses outweigh any profit made by the business. Anything that is accrued goes straight back into supporting others. When the individual 'stabilises' their life, we offer employment in a push to get them to sustain a healthy lifestyle and get off Centrelink benefits.

In 2015-2016, the activities of the History Council of Victoria (HCV) encouraged greater understanding and awareness of history. As the peak body for history in Victoria, the HCV provides a reference point for an understanding of history through its website and public activities. The HCV brings together the major bodies relating to (A) history and heritage in Victoria (Royal Historical Society of Victoria, Museums Australia (Vic), Professional Historians Association (Vic), Heritage Council of Victoria, Museum Victoria, National Trust of Australia Victoria, State Library Victoria, Public Record Office Victoria and Women's HERitage Centre Victoria), (B) the history teaching profession (via the History Teachers' Association of Victoria, the Victorian Curriculum and Assessment Authority and the state government's Department of Education and Training), (C) the media (Australian Broadcasting Corporation), and (D) the universities which teach history (currently, Deakin University, La Trobe University and Monash University).For general audiences, the HCV organised its Annual Lecture (22 Oct 2015) with support from Old Treasury Building and as part of the annual History Week. Professor Lynette Russell (Monash University) lectured on 'Australia's Big Science Picnic 1914: Some New Evidence'.For higher education and general audiences, the HCV collaborated with Monash University and State Library Victoria on 'Making Public Histories', a seminar series led by academic and professional historians. The seminars were: 'S. T. Gill as eyewitness: art as historical evidence' (29 Sep 2015); 'Melbourne's Alice: Lewis Carroll's Alice in Wonderland as source, artefact and inspiration in art, science and history' (26 Nov 2015); 'The Day that Shook Russell Street' (24 Mar 2016); and 'First drafts of History: Rediscovering Victoria's war correspondents' (21 Apr 2016).For schools, the HCV delivered the History Roadshow to Year 11 and 12 VCE students and their teachers in regional Victoria. A grant from the state Department of Education and Training through its Strategic Partnerships Program supported the program. With the involvement of leading historians in fields related to the students' curriculum, the Roadshow visited Rosebud, Geelong, Ballarat, Bendigo and Shepparton ' regional cities that serve as hubs for large numbers of schools.For students in Years 9 and 10, the HCV sponsored the Historical Fiction Competition organised by the History Teachers' Association of Victoria.For general and academic audiences, the HCV reached an agreement with Australian Scholarly Publishing to subsidise publication of 'A History of Victoria's State Secondary Education' (the working title for a manuscript commissioned by the HCV).The Board prepared a Strategic Plan for 2016-2019. column49: The Pascoe Vale RSL operates a Pension and Welfare Office which is entirely supported by 2 Volunteers. A large proportion of the cases prepared by the Pension Office are Veteran Affairs matters. In addition to veteran claims, the Pension Office also handles claims for serving members of the armed forces in respect to military compensation and rehabilitation service. The Pension and Welfare advocates act on behalf of veterans, war widows and current servicemen to ensure that they receive a fair hearing of their case or an outcome which they seek. The Pension and Welfare Office Advocates provide support to veterans who are seeking entitlements, based on their service, from the Department of Veteran Affairs. Furthermore the advocates investigate cases and provide advice on the merits of appeals and provide veterans with representation to the Veterans' Review Board. The Pension and Welfare Office, supported by the committee and office staff of the RSL provide the following assistance to veterans and families during family bereavement.  ÇProviding information about RSL funeral rituals, volunteers prepare and perform RSL rituals at funerals when required.  ÇProviding funeral assistance.  ÇProvision of laurel and poppies for a funeral service.  ÇProviding advice on Department of Veterans' Affairs entitlements.  ÇProviding advice on war grave entitlements.  ÇAssisting with war widow's claims. The Pascoe Vale RSL actively participates in the raising funds for the yearly run Poppy and Anzac Appeals. A band of volunteers made up of the RSL Committee and members sell poppies and badges and organise BBQs to raise money for the Appeals. Through support from our valuable volunteers, and donations from individuals, groups and businesses within our communities, we work towards achieving our mission and hope to give back to those who sacrificed their lives for our country. The RSL's Women's Auxiliary are a small band, who work voluntarily, to assist the Pascoe Vale R.S.L Sub Branch in raising funds to help our members. We rely on bingo, fund raisers such as fashion parades, trading tables, raffles, etc. and this year our Christmas Concert. The monies raised go to the Sub Branch to help in making our R.S.L a place for all members. Fundraisers held for MND and Biggest Morning Tea.

RWAV's mission is to develop and deliver solutions to enhance rural, regional and Aboriginal communities' access to health workforce. We recruited and placed 109 general practitioners (GPs) and 14 allied health professionals into rural and regional Victoria. We also provided workforce support to 406 rural general practices, 26 Aboriginal Community Controlled Health Services employing 1,883 GPs and Registrars. 176 GP locum placements were facilitated to allow for emergency and holiday relief for GPs and 4,129 sessions of medical services were provided to rural Victorian communities. 361 doctors were assisted to access CPD and training grants to undertake up skilling and further procedural training. We coordinated the delivery of outreach services to rural Victorian communities through 375 services that made 5,753 visits to rural Victorian communities and saw 70,027 patients in their own community negating the need for them to travel to Melbourne or regional centres for medical specialist and allied health services.

In 2016 Victorian Women Lawyers celebrated its 20th anniversary of assisting women working in the law and promoting the interests of women through the law. Over the course of the year, VWL has been committed to reaching out to members and potential members with a diverse range of events and initiatives. We have focused on ensuring that our association is welcoming and inclusive to women lawyers and law students from a diverse range of backgrounds and perspectives, whether that be cultural, socioeconomic, LGBTIQ, regional and suburban.  VWL delivered almost 40 events and projects that were aimed at examining topics that are important to our members. These included: pay transparency, family violence, revenge porn, addressing unconscious bias, closing the gender pay gap, incarceration of indigenous women, career progression, culturally sensitive legal advice, flexibility and tackling sexism, harassment and gender discrimination. A series of regional events in Geelong, Bendigo and Shepparton, as well as recording and posting videos of our events on our website, represented our efforts to reach out to regional women lawyers.  We continue to contribute to public discourse on law reform and policy. This year our Law Reform and Justice Committees made submissions to the Senate inquiries on the phenomenon colloquially known as 'revenge porn' and the Fair Work Amendment (Gender Pay Gap) Bill, as well as the Victorian Gender Equality Strategy.   In 2016, VWL matched a record number of 187 pairs of mentors and mentees in our Law Student Mentoring Program. The Program continues to be highly valuable to women who are preparing to enter the legal profession. The second annual Warren Moot saw over 30 VWL members participate in the competition with many adjudicators from the judiciary and the Bar generously donating their time to adjudicate the moot rounds.  Further information can be found in Portia 2016: the annual journal and report of Victorian Women Lawyers at https://vwl.asn.au/publications/

column49: National Exhibitions Touring Support (NETS) Victoria is the peak body for touring visual culture in the state of Victoria. NETS Victoria collaborates with art galleries, cultural institutions, artists and curators to co-create and co-present outstanding exhibitions and projects that are supported by engaging high quality publications and public and learning programs, which promote increased audience participation and educational engagement with contemporary art across regional Victoria.NETS Victoria incubates new projects across the state through the provision of seed funding the Exhibition Development Fund grants program. We provide regional galleries with best practice support services for our touring programs, free professional touring advice and support, and professional development opportunities for their staff. Through our program we build professional and community networks, fostering dialogue between our artists and curators and regional audiences and art practitioners.Organisational and project support is received from the Victorian Government through Creative Victoria, through the Federal Government's arts funding body the Australia Council for the Arts and via the Visions of Australia program from the Ministry for the Arts. As a Registered Cultural Organisation NETS Victoria also seeks public donations and bequests to support its artistic program and access initiatives.Over the last 20 years NETS Victoria has toured more than 70 exhibitions to over 370 destinations. Organisational records indicate that more than 2 million people have attended have NETS Victoria exhibitions since the early nineties.

Mai Foundation made a grant to YMCA Victoria to enable a pilot program entitled Youth for Causes which empowers teams of young people to create social enterprises for causes they care about.Teams of young people from five secondary schools in Victoria were selected to participate and receive training, mentorship and seed money to create a social enterprise.The program included a launch evening, a bootcamp to introduce social enterprise and how to communicate their idea to others, eight training sessions covering Communicating and Pitching Your Idea, Business Planning, Financials 101, Events and Fundraising, Marketing PR and Storytelling, Collaborations and Partnerships.The Mai Foundation Chairman, Michael Mai, provided volunteer business mentorship for one of the participating teams.The pilot program held a Project Showcase Awards and Celebration event in October 2016.Subsequent feedback and evaluation of the program from all participants was overwhelmingly positive.  Some of the markers of success included increased awareness of social enterprise, increased understanding of social and environmental issues in the community, gaining of skills relevant to starting and running a social enterprise, increased skills in problem solving, creativity, communication and engaging, teamwork,  budgeting and finance, marketing and communication, delivering presentations, business planning, planning and managing events, reporting and accountability. increased motivation to  start and support a social enterprise, increased skills and motivation to  get a job in the future, and enterprise profits being donated to charity.Additionally, Youth for Causes pilot created collaboration between the YMCA and YGAP, organisations that support and empower young people in Australia and overseas. Both organisations are major beneficiaries of grant money from Mai Foundation.These activities and outcomes fulfil Mai Foundation's charitable purpose to empower youth through venture philanthropy.

Family Life assists families, children and young people with a priority on helping those who are the most vulnerable. We aim to help make our society a better place for everyone. Family Life provides holistic, therapeutic and practical support services which we develop in response to the diverse needs of the community including culturally diverse groups and indigenous families. Our social enterprises demonstrate the power of community-owned businesses to provide pathways for recycling, reducing social isolation, enhancing community engagement and economic security. Family Life is a centre of research, knowledge and innovation. Our learning and evaluation strategy builds evidence for assessing impact, and informs our national advocacy for social change to prevent and solve social problems. At the heart of our work are the authentic grass-roots relationships with our people, the people we help and the people of the community. Together we provide effective care and connection for transforming lives.

As a catalytic philanthropic organisation, ten20 is all about bringing inspiration and innovation to early childhood investment in AU to ensure all children thrive in learning and life. Our purpose is to catalyse, convene and support community led collective impact efforts. Our singular focus is vulnerable children between the ages 0-8 over the next 10 years. Our bold goal is to work alongside partners to reduce AU's child vulnerability as per the Australian Early Development Census.Our strategy and principal activities relate to providing funding and support that creates enabling conditions to set up the Opportunity Child (OC) initiative for success. OC's bold goal is to dramatically change the lives of the 65,000 five-year-old children who start school in AU each year with big challenges in learning and in life. Ten20 focuses on influencing the system through building partnerships, funding, capacity, and trust, playing a key role in stewardship, innovation and sustainability of early childhood investments.Ten20 works closely with, and is part of the OC Collective, comprised of various communities and organisations across AU in partnership and collaboration, together aligning individual  strategies and activities for collective impact and to deliver shared values and better outcomes in early childhood. This collective impact approach develops new ways of working together, innovation that leads systems to change.As a Collective, some highlights of activities and outcomes achieved in 2016: Ç Developed the OC initiative's shared strategy and vision, delivered in the five key activity areas: Collective, Learning, Impact, Capital and Voice.  Ç Developed the OC data measurement and outcomes framework for partner communities, which is framed with the overarching national shared outcomes framework, reflecting state based efforts, including the NEST (part of the Australian Research Alliance for Children and Youth) and Results Based Accountability frameworks and Efforts to Outcomes enabling technology.  Ç Strengthened our voice with improved outreach campaigns such as a new website, social media, and regular distribution of ten20 Concentric and OC enews. This informs about the latest developments in our work and influences early childhood investment in AU by encouraging new forms of thinking, funding and solutions, create more opportunities and resources for all. Ç Advocated for change in systems, practices and mindset through speaking at public dialogue and presentations, eg. the Leadership Conference in Canberra, the Asian Venture Philanthropy Conference, influential Discussion Panels and Funder Roundtables across AU Ç In partnership with the Harwood Institute for Public Innovation in the US, developed the 'Funder Roadmap__, a tool to support others who seek to undertake a collective impact approach and other funders looking to align and in need of a road-map to more effectively align with the communities that they serve and to de-risk the work.

Sustainable Table has pursued its charitable purpose in the following ways:GIVE  A FORK! ' We delivered our largest ever behaviour change and awareness campaign Give a Fork!, during April 2016 (www.giveafork.com.au). This campaign focussed on bringing about positive environmental change through the food we eat. The campaign gets people thinking about the environmental and ethical impact of the food we buy, whilst bringing the sexy back into caring. As part of the campaign we coined the term grexy (green + sexy = sexy greenie), as a way to draw attention to the fact that taking care of the planet is way sexier than trashing it.The four pillars of the campaign were to promote a food system that's fair, humane, healthy and good for the environment.298 people signed up to a 30 days to '#grexy' challenge which encouraged participants to change their everyday eating habits and reduce landfill waste to reduce their impact on the planet. 91% of respondents said they would sign up again next year. Survey feedback concluded that 83% reduced meat intake, 80% of people no longer order coffee in a disposable cup, 77% reduced plastic packaging, 60% now ask for their drink without a straw or carry their own and 41% of participants now take their own containers to the shops, which further reduces landfill waste.As part of Give a Fork! we also recruited 101 restaurants to participate in the campaign by developing and promoting an environmentally conscious specials dish(es) based on our '4 Food Rules' for sustainability. Almost 10,000 specials were sold!Encouraging restaurant participation had multiple benefits. First and foremost, hospitality venues are huge buyers of food and thus can influence the sustainability of supply chains as well as influence how people choose to eat not just out, but also at home.The campaign reached 4.7 million people through PR activities with editorial articles and blogs highlighting the importance of being environmentally conscious through food, reducing plastic packaging and food waste and supporting farmers by purchasing seasonal produce from farmers' markets.PUBLISHED WRITING - Sustainable Table developed content for reputable blogs and magazines that promoted reducing waste and reducing our eco-footprint through ethical eating. Publications and blogs included Dumbo Feather, Real Estate.com.au and Nourish Magazine (see Annual Report for more info).EVENTS AND WORKSHOPS - Sustainable Table ran a number of events, workshops and participated in guest speaking engagements to educate people on food sustainability, which included topics such as; Reducing landfill waste and plastic pollution through our food choices, what is sustainable and ethical eating?, reducing food waste at home, supporting ecological farmers and screenings of Plastic Paradise and our own documentary Waste Deep. Through these events we reached and educated an audience of over 2,000 people. http://sustainabletable.org.au/Portals/0/Sustainable%20Tab

column49: The primary function of Aspire Training and Consulting Limited is to promote and facilitate skills development to ensure an adequate supply of skilled staff to meet the long-term needs of industry. We do this by creating resources that underpin skill development, focussing on supporting high risk, under resourced and fast growing areas where there are skill gaps in the workforce, particularly in transport & logistics, construction and children services as well as foundation skills that underpin development of any skills. Aspire focuses on a wide range of learner groups including; those with insufficient language and literacy skills, early school leavers, disaffected youth with learning and social issues, those at risk of facing long-term unemployment, those returning to the workforce, those in rural/remote areas, those wanting recognition of existing skills, and those who are already employed but want to advance their careers and build new skills.Development and provision of learning and support resources to develop new skills and or build on existing skills to support a skilled workforce is a priority of Aspire. We work with Service Skills Organisations as a source of information and services to support their successful transition into the vocational education market. Our foundation will continue to provide opportunities for disadvantaged learners/groups to develop vocational skills leading to further training or employment; we will continue to develop vocational education resources to support the acquisition of foundation and vocational skills and will act as a source of valuable information to government bodies, educators and industry on VET issues.Aspire continued supporting the work experience program for refugees run by the Migrant Resource Centre. This program has been very successful since Aspire started supporting it in 2012, with a number of participants transitioning from their placements to employment. Aspire also provided funding for a new program run by the disability support service Onemda, called Caf© Ability offering hospitality training opportunities for young people with an intellectual disability. This program has been well run and successful, with great outcomes for the participants, particularly two who have entered employment.  Soon we will work with the Sir David Martin Foundation to support their Accredited Vocational and Educational Training program, run for disadvantaged youth attending the rehabilitation facility Triple Care Farm as well as supporting the Onemda Mobile Training Caf©: Training Program. This is an extension of their prior programs, which provides training for young disabled learners to work in a mobile caf© operating in the local community. The Victorian Principals Association conducted a comprehensive range of activities to help achieve its purpose of advancing education and public debate.  Through these activities the Association aims to be instrumental in optimizing the educational opportunities and outcomes for students in all government primary schools in Victoria.  To build leadership capacity in the sector, the VPA offered a high quality Professional Learning program to both members and non-members.  In 2015 - 2016 this included:  -  running and subsidizing over 35 full day workshops that encompassed the many aspects of school leadership. -  an Annual Conference with a two day program of renowned presenters and opportunities for collegiate discussions and networking.  -  the Principals as Literacy Leaders program involving five modules and ten hours follow up coaching for each participant.   This year 85 school leaders were involved in this program.  - a 16 day student study tour to China for 50 students and their teachers which provided outstanding opportunities for cultural exchange and understanding, language acquisition and personal development.   - a highly successful program for aspiring leaders.  - a Statewide Forum which included speakers who presented on a range of key areas in education and was attended by 160 schools leaders from across the state.   Another important aspect of the VPA's work is its advocacy role of advancing public debate in the education field.  This has involved the VPA representing the views and concerns of Victorian government primary school leaders and providing expert advice to government.  To this effect, the VPA was involved on an ongoing basis in government consultations, stakeholder groups and meetings with the various sections of the education department and associated government departments, with Ministers of Educations and other political leaders and with other professional groups and stakeholders.  The VPA has provided information and advice to school leaders through its Member Advisor service, a weekly VPA Newsletter and its website.   Collegiate networking has been facilitated by regular regional meetings where information about government initiatives and effective approaches to teaching and learning, student and staff welfare and school leadership are discussed and shared.   This year 37 such meetings were organised.  A particular focus for the VPA has been supporting smaller rural and remote schools to participate in professional learning.  Twenty scholarships were offered for leaders of these schools to attend the Annual Conference and casual relief teachers were funded to release teaching principals from their classes, enabling them to attend professional learning programs.  The VPA also facilitated four study awards for school leaders to explore initiatives in other states or countries that have direct relevance to students at their own schools.

column2: The Field Naturalists Club Of Victoria Inc
column39: The FNCV has eight special interest groups (SIGS) through which its activities are conducted. Fungi, Geology, Marine research, Microscopy, Terrestrial Invertebrates and Juniors.  These SIGS are engaged in education and research through activities, meetings, projects and publications.  The FNCV also publishes 6 editions of the Victorian Naturalist a year - a refereed journal.
column49: The 8 special interest groups listed in Section B above are  engaged in education and research through activities, meetings, surveys and publications.  The Fauna Survey group and the Marine research Group in particular,  but also other groups contribute to animal protection through their surveys, eg. the long running survey of Leadbeaters Possum in the central highlands and the ongoing Rushworth Survey,  The group has recently worked closely with Parks Victoria on projects s at Baal Baal,  Annuello, Metropolitan Melbourne parks etc.  All surveys are carried out under permit and the results are lodged with the appropriate body. The Fungi group has discovered  many new fungi species in Victoria and has contributed enormously to Fungimap.  Marine research has discovered new species and monitored the spread of pest species.   FNCV educates the public through its regular meetings through the 6 editions of the Victorian Naturalist published a year year - a refereed journal.  and through other publications such as 3 fungi DVD's.  The Juniors group introduces and educates  children from 5 to 18 to all aspects of natural history.  Over 50 families belong to the Juniors group.   All this is achieved by Volunteers.  The only paid person in the FNCV is an office administrator who works 2 and a half days a week. There is a lot more I could add to how this organisation achieves its purposes. Please read about its comprehensive program at fncv.org.au

column49: Deafness Foundation grants program is focussed towards achieving the purpose to improve wellbeing and promote equality for people who are deaf and hard of hearing by focussing on 1:  Access; 2:  Awareness; and 3:  Diagnosis, treatment and prevention.  The key priority areas for the Foundation are 1:  Minimising the incidence of preventable hearing loss;2:  Enhancing awareness of issues for people who are deaf or hard of hearing;3:  Strengthening and building partnerships and collaborative relationships;4:  Supporting people with hearing loss5:  Serving Australia wide.The Annual Grants Program provides funding to enable organisations across Australia to fund resources which benefit specifically their local communities.  This years grants included an Audiology Resource Booklet designed for Indigenous clients in the Barwon region; an Early Intervention program for children with partial hearing loss; a Sound & Light Integration Project at a school in NSW to assist students to recognise timings, etc. (eg by flashing lights); funding of an Online Hub for Musicians 4 Hearing to provide hearing awareness materials for musicians and gig-goers.   The opportunity to assist rural communities is vital to enabling those with a hearing loss to be included via the funding of a Soundfield System in the Church Hall; thus providing amplification for activities undertaken at the Hall, be they weddings, funerals, activities or community meetings.  The soundfield system is portable and can be moved from the church to the hall.  Our Grants program has funded significant research outcomes including a Hearing element of the ASPREE Project and the Peter Howson Clinical Research Fellowship for the 2016-17 period to Dr Kerryn Saunders on Early Identification and Management of Congenital Cytomegalovirus Hearing Loss / A New Clinical Model.  Congenital Cytomegalovirus (or cCMV) is a significant cause of deafness in babies.

column49: Lighthouse activities centre on three core priorities (i.e. Presence, Position & Performance) across all business divisions (i.e. Governance, Administration, Facilities/Support & Science. All divisions are dependent on each-others respective activities & appropriately balanced to be consistent, attainable, sustainable & expandable. In addition, our efforts sought to assure effectiveness & efficiency plus, best practice to meet the aspirations/expectations of all.  Our re-emergence from an imposed period of hiatus has continued to gather impetus & ground ' Notably in regard to our core priorities being progressively accomplished in many divisional activities. However, our research aspirations in terms of laboratory performance & outcome are still in need of more funding, to support our research endeavours. In prelude & in-keeping with our position priority, we have sought access to public research venues & considered the establishment of a private autonomous research facility as backup (i.e. in the event that space at a public venue is denied or not available). In addition, we have outreached to research peers for cooperation & commenced recruitment of our research team to help with project planning preparations.  It is anticipated that Lighthouse will have completed its re-emergence phase with research performance & outcomes demonstrated in the coming financial year.  A budget with diversified revenue streams circa $500k PA is sought to underpin a critical mass. This mass will include several senior investigators plus, 10-20 post-graduate investigators co funded & co-supervised with partner groups to expand research scope & themes. Re-establishing a WA head-quarter & satellite operations interstate is also planned. Key objects, aims & outcomes are summarized as follows:Object 1 Rekindle fundraising & in turn cash-flow to underpin core activities that facilitate research.Outcome: Four WA permit raffles were completed - An audit also undertaken. Charitable collection licences were applied/re-applied for (approved in the new financial year) ' Fundraising primarily occurred at WA shopping centres & to a lesser degree via pilot social media & crowd funding outreach programs interstate.Object 2 Improve the financial position, i.e. reducing liabilities, increasing assets, utilising volunteers & minimising expenditure.Outcome: The balance sheet is moving in a positive direction. Volunteers contributed 4000hrs using their own personal resources. Object 3 Explore & enable researchOutcome: Proposals & correspondence were prepared & presented to public research establishments & key government research authorities/officials - Research peers were engaged to explore opportunity for cooperation/collaboration - Recruitment drives for research personnel were implemented ' A conference was attended ' Pending research programs & projects have been planned, considered & explored. A detailed annual report will be appear on a pending revised website

mecwacare had a significant strategic focus on service growth, development and geographic expansion in 2015-2016 as we entered a new era of consumer-directed care in both the aged care and disability sectors. To be sustainable in this new era organisations need to focus on growth, with larger organisations having greater resources and an increased capacity to adapt to changing funding models and government regulatory and reporting requirements. This is especially true for not-for-profit (NFP) organisations such as mecwacare, where the alternative to growth is merger or consolidation of smaller providers. This can in turn result in a reduced 'local community' service focus, a traditional strength of NFP providers. With this imperative for service growth in mind, the past year saw a range of growth outcomes achieved, with each of our primary services ' Home Nursing and Care Services, Home Care Packages, Residential Services, Community Housing Services and Community and Disability Services ' growing substantially and taking significant steps towards future expansion. We were successful in 11 tenders over the past financial year that related to service provision, growing client choice and geographic coverage across Residential Services, Home Nursing and Care Services and Home Care Packages. We expanded our Residential Services to 11 facilities as we welcomed an additional 312 residents to mecwacare. We now have a residential presence in regional Victoria with facilities in Hamlyn Heights (Geelong), in Traralgon in the Latrobe Valley, and in Terang in Western Victoria, alongside the expanded Home Nursing and Care South West Region Service operating from the Ballarat office. This acquisition boosts mecwacare's capacity to over 700 beds in 11 facilities, and advances mecwacare's five-year strategic plan for growth and sustainability into a Victoria-wide service provider. In the past year mecwacare completed two new builds totaling 50 new Community Housing units. We now provide 89 high quality, long-term affordable homes for financially or socially disadvantaged older people or people with a disability at three locations.  We continued to expand the program variety of mecwacare's Community Services at our day centres, with the growth reflected in increased client attendance at both sites. A specialised dementia-specific program began at our Bowen Street Centre in Malvern East, with staff receiving training suited to the special needs of people living with dementia. A complementary new program at the centre provides a social respite to carers of loved ones with dementia. A clinical focus of the organisation has been on end-of-life advance care planning and palliative care, with mecwacare undertaking a long-term project to increase our staff knowledge, improve our clinical processes and client and family experience, and make a substantial contribution to palliative care best practice across our services and the sector more widely.

Destiny Care provides Food support for disadvantaged people in the City of Kingston and surrounding suburbs.  Our food support includes Hampers for singles, couples and families, with ingredients to prepare nutritious meals for at least a couple of days, including fresh fruit and vegetables; fresh dairy, bread; frozen food; staple items such as rice and pasta; canned soups; cereals.  Our hampers are made up according to clients' dietary and religious needs, as well as the size of their family.  We endeavour to vary the non-refrigerated components of our hampers on a fortnightly basis, so that our regular clients are able to access a varied diet.  Last year we assisted people from 47 different nations, and gave away over 2800 food hampers.  Each Wednesday we also provide a drop-in centre from 10am'3pm, supplying morning tea, and a free, cooked, 2 course lunch for those clients who wish to attend.  Here they receive a nutritious and tasty meal, as well as the chance to mix with each other, make friends and receive emotional support from our volunteers and/or each other.  From our interactions with our clients, we know that for some, this lunch provides the largest boost to their nutrition levels each week, due to the amount of vegetables we try to pack into each meal.

Supporting Our Families:  Leukodystrophy Australia is aware of nearly 250 families or individuals affected by a leukodystrophy across Australia.  Assistance:  To families - newly diagnosed and beyond; emotional support; advocacy to assist connection with relevant services; equipment and aids; direct financial support where possible, through volunteers, counselling and peer support.  Raising Awareness:  As Leukodystrophy remains an under-diagnosed and misunderstood condition, Leukodystrophy Australia is committed to raising awareness of the condition.   To do this, we have maintained a website and Facebook presence; we held a 20th Anniversary Conference; we continued to publish a quarterly Newsletter with a circulation of approximately 500; we support various fundraising events; and have provided guest speakers for presentations, where members of Leukodystrophy Australia have related their personal stories.  Encouraging Research:  Leukodystrophy Australia contributes to research into Leukodystrophy where funds and opportunity allow.  We established a close connection with UNSW's Dr Matthias Klugmann (2014), whose work includes gene therapy research into the leukodystrophies; we provided placements for students undertaking relevant courses at various universities; and we initiated a 'Clinicians and Researcher Network (Leukodystrophy and Leukoencephalopathy)' network, comprising doctors and scientists in 5 states. www.leuko.org.au

The Cure for MND Foundation runs fundraising activities throughout the year to raise awareness and funds for Motor Neurone Disease (MND). It is our vision to live in a world without MND and we aim to raise the profile of MND within Australia and abroad in the hopes that increased awareness may lead to not only better care for those affected by the disease, but also increased funding for vital research into finding a cure.Through events such as the Big Freeze and the Daniher's Drive we have been able to fund 16 research grants across Australia. We are also the trial sponsors for the first two Australian-led clinical trials for MND. The Cure for MND Foundation has launched two grant schemes with funds available for 2017. Firstly, our Translational Research Grants are available for Australian MND Researchers and are aimed at funding pre-clinical testing of 'ready-to-go' compounds according to the strict, standardised guidelines of the ALS-Therapy Development Institute (ALS-TDI) or supporting drug development and manufacturing of therapies that have strong efficacy data. Grants are awarded for 3 years up to the value of $1 million. Our second grant scheme is aimed at funding Phase II clinical trials. These grants will fund Australian run clinical trials of therapies that have already been tested in Phase I (safety and tolerability) or Phase II (safety and efficacy) trials in MND patients overseas. These are available internationally and for amounts up to $1.5 million dollars. Furthermore, in 2017, the Cure for MND Foundation will be the largest single funder of new assistive equipment for Australian's living with MND. The Foundation has committed $1.25million to help current MND patients and their families deal with the struggles that a diagnosis of MND brings.

Each year in Australia: 5,500 people die from alcohol related injuries, illness and accidents. 157,000 people are hospitalised due to alcohol. More people die from drug overdoses, including from pharmaceuticals, than die on the roads. The cost to the community from alcohol-related harm is estimated to exceed $15.3 billion. For illegal drugs it exceeds $8.2 billion.Research shows that creating connected communities is the key to preventing alcohol and drug problems. In these communities people feel valued, supported and purposeful.We design and deliver a range of community programs, services and resources targeted at preventing alcohol and other drug-related harm. We know that healthy and resilient communities are the best way to prevent substance use problems. Our programs work to prevent harm in specific environments, changing practices and attitudes to create safer places for people to live, work and play.Our Good Sports program is the first program of its kind to be proven successful in the world ' so we know it works. There are currently over 7,000 clubs involved in the Good Sports Program, making it Australia's largest sport-based health initiative. Participation in the program has been shown to greatly reduce the odds of risky drinking in clubs. Good Sports clubs are 42% less likely to experience alcohol-related harms in clubs. In NSW, we have a program where the community has a real opportunity to make a difference in their local area through joining a Community Drug Action Team to take action to prevent Alcohol and Drug related harm. In collaboration with NSW Health and local agencies, we have produced a suite of resources that will help educate communities about crystalline methamphetamine ('ice').

column39: Motoring and Corporate Events
column49: Variety empowers Australian children who are sick, disadvantaged or have special needs to live laugh and learn.  Our vision is for all Australian children to reach their full potential regardless of ability or background.  In 2016 Variety Victoria directly impacted 2155 children across Victoria by providing grants through our three key programs - Freedom, Future and Caring for Kids.  We provided 67 grants through our Freedom program, helping 1851 children gain independence by providing financial support for mobility equipment, positioning and in-home care needs.  This includes the provision of custom modified tricycle and bikes, wheelchairs, specialist car seats and more.  We provided 43 grants through our Future Kids program helping 7117 children realize their potential by providing financial support for education and communication equipment. This includes the provision of specialist computer packages, communication devices, scholarships, camps, regional and special education school support, sensory playgrounds,   and more. We provided 8 grants through our Caring for Kids program, by providing 187 children with medical items and care equipment so that sick children can live happy, healthy lives. This includes nebulisers, electric beds for families at home, supporting paediatric hospital wards, children's respite and rehabilitation centres and more.

Thomastown West Kindergarten is recognised as servicing a disadvantaged community. On the socio-economic index for areas (SEIFA) Thomastown is listed in the lowest 20% for Victoria. A majority of the families at this Kindergarten are amongst some of the most financially disadvantaged families in our municipality. Most families are concession card holders (50%+) and new immigrants including refugees and asylum seekers. Many children come from single parent families, have unemployed parents and several families are supported by Protective Services, Child First and Early Start funding. We also have children supported by KIS funding. Our charity purpose is to ensure local families and children have access to universal high quality educational preschool programs. We are continuously at capacity and provide a low or no fee educational service for families along with building links with other charity organisation and schools supporting our vulnerable community. Our charity status provides us with ongoing financial sustainability to provide quality community educational services.

Piloted the 'Sunday Walks in Tarneit' project in partnership with Wyndham City Council to develop and promote seven walking maps to support residents to overcome personal barriers to walking. Produced 24 high-quality digital walking maps for Latrobe City Council's new ParkTracks app.Worked directly in primary schools to increase walking levels of students. Held Walk the Block workplace walking event and Smart Steps for Business campaign to combat workplace physical inactivity.Generated over 120 media stories on walking issues.Presented at numerous conference and forums; participated in a number of government workshops and committees; and prepared a number of submissions to Victorian Government agencies and local councils to promote urban planning and infrastructure that supports walkability.Expanded social media presence, providing valuable platforms for public engagement on walking, health and liveability

Through our months of hard work in 2016 we have been able to meet the expectations we had put forward via our mission statement Enriching the lives of companion animals by reducing overpopulation, increasing adoptions and engaging the hearts, hands and minds of the community.

The Australian Children's Literature Alliance is responsible for the Australian Children's Laureate Program. The Laureate is an outstanding author and member of the Australian Children's Literature community who by example and through a rigorous touring program inspires children to develop and expand their interest and understanding of literature and of story Every two years a new Children's Laureate is announced and act as a national and international ambassador for reading. This work builds the foundation of culture in our society and inculcates a love of reading in young people.  More broadly, children all across Australia who have access to the Laureate, through school visits, festival attendances, regional touring programs, creative projects, social media and traditional media.A particular focus of the Laureate program has been working with children and families with low levels of literacy and children living in the remotest areas of Australia who would not readily have the chance to 'touch' literature up close and be inspired by Australia's most talented and engaging storytellers.

column2: The Trustee For Echo-elderly Citizens Help Organisation Inc.
column49: The focus of ECHO Inc is essentially to assist persons in Victoria who through misfortune cannot help themselves and have missed out from the welfare system. To undertake such a task in a small way requires funds. ECHO has assisted other charities in intersection tin shake collections building up expertise and knowledge in the field. The outcome of this program is that scarce funds are collected and distributed to much needed causes; the collectors themselves feel a net worth and self esteem in not only raising funds but also earning income rather than being on welfare.During the past year the money raised by ECHO which was not forwarded to partner charity organisations was used to purchase or trade in medical aids such as electric wheelchairs, walkers and shower aids. These are products for which there are extended waiting lists from different levels of Government. We were able to source and place two electric wheel chairs which were provided to housebound clients.Another activity we have has been the receipt of donated goods for distribution to those less fortunate. We have an active blanket program in the Winter and we provide some food relief to those in need who are drawn to our attention. A number of our collectors have not had the benefit of education and in this fast tech world are left behind. We are assisting some of these people to access programs which they are entitled to through local Library computers .There is much more to be done and if we can expand our fundraising then we shall be able to do more in the future
